title: MENA Golf Tour: Blomstrand goes two clear at Muscat Hills
text:
MENA Golf Tour: Blomstrand goes two clear at Muscat Hills Christofer Blomstrand tees off at Muscat Hills on Tuesday Muscat Daily staff writer October 21, 2015 
MENA Golf Tour debutants Christofer Blomstrand and Julian Kunzenbacher firmly put themselves in pole position on Tuesday, heading into the final round of the Muscat Hills Golf Citizen Championship. 
Sweden’s Blomstrand backed up his opening round of 67 with a solid 68 to reach nine under for the tournament, just two clear of Germany’s Kunzenbacher as the pair left many regular contenders trailing in their wake at the Muscat Hills Golf & Country Club. 
Morocco’s Younes El Hassani carded back-to-back 69s to move into a tie for third on six-under along with Australia’s Ryan Smith. A four-man group, led by Sweden’s Per Barth, won the Sheikh Maktoum Dubai Open last month, shared fifth a further shot adrift. 
Attributing his solid allround golf to warm weather, Blomstrand said, “I find it a lot easier to swing in these conditions. 
Barring early hiccups when I bogeyed a couple of holes, I think I played really well, tee to green, and holed some good putts, especially the one on the 16th that I sank from 16 feet.” 
“This event has provided me with a perfect opportunity to warm up for the second stage of the European Tour qualifier. With so many players shooting well, it just shows how good the standard of golf on the tour is,” said the 23 year old from Skanor, Sweden. 
Kunzenbacher, the 22 year old German, eagled the par-five 13th, smashing his six-iron from 200 yards to within 40 centimetres of the pin. 
El Hassani leads the MENA division by four shots from his compatriot Mehdi Saissi. 
Scottish youngster Ben Alexander, who shared the overnight lead with Blomstrand, Stuart Archibald and Cyril Suk after opening with a 67, stumbled to a 76, but managed to stay in front in the amateur division at one under par where he is joined by India’s Rayhan Thomas, who followed his opening 70 with a 73. 
The cut was made at four over 148 with 45 professionals and ten amateurs making it to the final round. 
Oman's Azaan al Rumhy made a quiet exit as he carded 79 for a total of 16 over par 160. Similar content
